Senator Moffitt
1 moves to amend the bill on page 12, lines 32-43, by rewriting those lines to read:
2 "(1) Fifty percent (50%) for local school administrative unit capital outlay
3 purposes, as defined in G.S. 115C-426(f), or to retire any indebtedness
4 incurred by the County for these purposes, and for local school administrative
5 unit operating expenses. Prior to any funds allocated under this subdivision
6 being used for local school administrative unit operating expenses, the
7 Buncombe County Board of Commissioners must provide the Buncombe
8 County Board of Education and the Ashville City Board of Education the
9 opportunity to present at a public meeting the impacts of not using those funds
10 on school capital projects. The Commission shall serve in an advisory capacity
11 to the Buncombe County Board of County Commissioners with respect to the
12 use of funds under this subdivision for school capital outlay purposes by
13 considering the capital needs of both the Buncombe County School System
14 and the Asheville City School System, prioritizing those needs, and
15 recommending projects to be funded. However, the use of funds under this
16 subdivision shall not be under the control of the Commission and shall be
17 determined by the Board of Commissioners.
18 (2) Fifty percent (50%) for any public purpose.
19 SECTION 16.1.(c) To the extent Buncombe County receives any federal or State
20 disaster funding as revenue replacement, the county shall return a proportionate share of revenue
21 replacement funds to the Commission up to the amount of diverted funds under this section. The
22 proportionate share shall be equal to the amount of revenue replacement received divided by the
23 County's total revenue loss multiplied by the amount of diverted funds. Any remaining funds
24 shall be used for any purposes allowed by the granting entity. For purposes of this subsection,
25 the following definitions apply:
26 (1) Revenue replacement. – Grant monies to compensate for tax or fee revenue
27 lost as the result of the impacts of Hurricane Helene to the extent the monies
28 are unrestricted in use and available for any public purpose.
29 (2) Total revenue loss. – Tax and fee revenue projected in the county budget for
30 FY 2024-2025 that was not realized due to the impacts of Hurricane Helene.
31 (3) Diverted funds. – The total amount of funds distributed by the Secretary of
32 Revenue to Buncombe County under subsection (a) of this section and used
